1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,000
Welcome to the Community Event Planner. Every number on screen comes from a Postgres view generated from one rulebook.

2
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:12,000
Header-based login with four dev roles. We'll pick Admin so we can show the edit flow later.

3
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:22,000
The dashboard. Four stat boxes — each an aggregation over the Events table: total, ready to publish, attendees, and events with issues.

4
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:32,000
Below, four upcoming events. Each row shows speakers, attendees, seats left, and a calculated status. Yellow flags mark venue conflicts.

5
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:40,000
Now the interesting part. I turn on provenance mode. Every derived value gets a function glyph showing it was computed, not stored.

6
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:52,000
Clicking 'Ready to Publish' opens the explainer for Events dot EventStatus. The formula is an IF over HasSpeakers, AtCapacity, and HasVenueConflict — three sub-calculations with their own DAGs.

7
00:00:52,000 --> 00:01:02,000
Back, then 'Total Attendees'. This opens BookedCapacity — a COUNTIFS aggregation over RSVPs filtered to confirmed status.

8
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:10,000
Back to the dashboard. Provenance off, and into tech-talk-1.

9
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:22,000
The Event Status block breaks the status into a checklist: speakers, capacity, venue conflicts. Every check or X is itself a calculated field.

10
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:32,000
Further down, Registration. Deadline and Open or Closed are both calculated from the close-days setting and the current time.

11
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:44,000
As admin I get a pencil to edit. The form changes raw inputs — name, venue, date, duration, close window, category.

12
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:56,000
Watch this: I change Registration Closes from one day to thirty days before. One raw field, RegistrationCloseDaysBeforeEvent.

13
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:02,000
Save fires a PATCH. The view recomputes. UI updates — no frontend math.

14
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:10,000
Now the Speakers tab — a calculated view over the Speakers table.

15
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:20,000
Each speaker shows an AssignmentCount aggregation. If anyone went over three, the page would surface an Overbooked warning at the top.

16
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:29,960
Last hop: clicking AssignmentCount opens its DAG — an aggregation over Assignments. Every number you saw came from the rulebook.
